<Review>Pretty cool place. It's got a good size arcade, about 12 bowling lanes, a bar for the adults, snack place to get something to eat and some pool tables. It's a nice addition to the mall and I'm happy to have it close to me. I only played around in the arcade with the kids and it's a little expensive. The use the reloadable cards like most places do now. I like that all your "tickets" get added to the card so you don't have to carry them around. I didn't like that some games cost a fraction of a credit. I know it's a way to keep you playing and always have credits on the card but really why should a game cost 6.8 credits. Just make sure you keep the card so you don't have to buy another one after your first  purchase. All in all it a nice clean place and all the games I played worked so that's always a plus. I say go and check it out.< /Review>< Pics>

<Rate>3< /Rate><Text>This review is based on comparison to the Japan round 1 establishment. Unfortunately I came here with high expectations of having a great experience like I did at the round one establishments I attended  while I lived in Japan. $25 in Japan gets you access to three floors of arcades, darts, pool halls, ping pong, boxing, indoor skating, batting cage, basketball courts, archery just to name a few.

Unfortunately this is just like a Dave and busters, memberships and different level player club cards. You can get a $10 card for 60 min unlimited game play at anything that lights up green, however most of them are old games that not many want to play. Getting the multicolor is the best option if you want to enjoy the entire establishment but expect to pay a good amount  for that access.

The place is conviniently located at the mall. The crowd was normal, not a lot of wait time to play video games, small bowling alley and pool hall.

It would be great if they would apply some of the Japan business practices. Perhaps getting a bigger place maybe the 2nd floor?

Anyways overall a good spot to take your kids or go have a drink and play games with friends.<//Text><user_id>100476365517296392012</user_id>< user_name>

Fun place to play pool or bowling. The games are expensive, just be aware, but are usually always working. We rarely play the games, almost always play Pool. The Pool tables are clean and we'll taken care of. It's fairly easy to grab a beer and enjoy yourself. One downside is the extremely loud and constant announcements, reminding you they don't serve alcohol to minors. Another is the food is bland, not bad, just bland. The staff is always ready to help.<//review>

AVOID AT ALL COSTS!
management is a joke, and disrespectful. I made a complaint about the service of the bartender, or lack there of, and was mocked and harassed by Eric the manager who used foul language when conversing with me. I am not sensitive to that but it is extremely unprofessional, I was shocked and even made a comment to Eric about how unprofessional it was and he continued to do it. After nothing of our dispute was settled Eric left, later on we were refused service from the bar with no explanation, the assumption we‚Äôve made is because we complained. That is textbook harassment and retaliation in the eyes of EEO and customer service. We requested the manager to return, he had a snarky attitude and continued to use foul language and offered to fix nothing. He could not provide us with a reason we were being denied service, then eventually came up with the lie that we were causing problems and wasting his employees time. The people in the lanes around us were laughing at this statement, we were all pretty much in shock. I didn‚Äôt know this was a COMMUNIST establishment. I was blunt but respectful and never threatening towards the manager and he eventually threatened me saying that the police were outside and he didn‚Äôt want to have to call them in. This was a hysterical statement and I immediately welcomed the company of our boys in blue. The officer approaches and I apologized for the establishment wasting his time. The officer stayed for about 15 seconds and said maybe 2 words and it seemed he has history with this place and these managers. Eric then asked us to leave and kicked us out forfeiting the rest of our bowling time, no reason was offered other than that we were causing problems. Apparently if you complain you are causing problems.

After all that, if you like bowling the lanes suck and the scoring is glitchy, lighting is terrible as well.

And if you‚Äôre doubting the character of our crowd, we are professionals and act accordingly. We had a police officer, nurse, fire fighter and two Physician Assistants in our group.

Finally, this was the worst experience I have ever had at an establishment hands down, don‚Äôt complain or they will call the police and kick you out. Eric is a joke of a manager, completely worthless and had no idea what being a manager entails.

Also, this was the short version of or story, there was many other smaller factors that play into our review, I honestly can‚Äôt think of one good thing to say about this place.

< Text>
If you're a fan of Dave & Buster's, then just make the extra drive and go there and skip this place. It's really expensive. It takes a lot of tokens per game, and for little yield on tickets. The games remind me phone apps blown up super size. Nothing exciting. There's no restaurant like D&B has. You have to go to a kiosk, type in your order, pay, then take the paid ticket to the counter and they will prepare food. Then they call a number and you can pick up your food to eat. not that the food in Dave and Buster's is fantastic or anything, but this food is definitely subpar. There is extremely limited seating. I think there are three booths and a handful of tables. Again, if you're looking more of a D&B experience then do the drive because it's much better. Oh, and the A/C was off or set too high. It was STIFLING in there!< /Text>

The Bowling alley was clean and tidy. The shoes you have to rent are all new. The attendant removed balls as people left. The pool tables are new and tournament size. <Text>This relatively new arcade opened in the Promenade mall where downstairs Sears use to be. It's nice on the inside. There are arcade games, claw machine games, a prize center, bar for alcoholic drinks, and bowling lanes. This place usually seems to be busy and this holds true on weekends. The facilities are pretty clean for the amount of people who are in the building which is always a positive. The only downside would be the lack of space to move around since many of the arcade machines are close to each other. Prices for "tokens" are also expensive given its location in the mall. Overall I would highly recommend, even if you dont play any games it's still fun to walk around there an see all the games they offer.</Text><time>1576954462828<//time></record>

</record></dataset><record>
< review>
Sometimes I can't stand the Temecula/Murrieta snobbery. This arcade is one of the best In southern california hands down. People complain about the food and drink here just to give it 1 star and yet theres 50 other restaurants within walking distance...People are clearly missing the point. The arcade encourages people to interact and meetup, which is something our society needs more of. All the machines were in clean and perfect working order and the temperature was a comfortable 70ish, which can be tough to maintain in an arcade.  People don't just come here to bowl...they come here to have fun and entertain themselves, so stop complaining about the lack of official bowling league floorwax thickness etc... They also have private party rooms which have sound dampening, and most impotantly RENTABLE KARAOKE ROOMS. The Redemption tickets are stored on a card, so no need to carry buckets of tickets around anymore. Even better is that the prizes are actually good, they are not just an overpriced walmart radio/alarm clock, tootsie rools, green army men, or chinese finger traps. Take some time to see what this place does well and you'll have a blast!< /review>

<UserId.>105655443252437935388</UserId.>< name>
Alex Furr< /name>
<time>1554181029633<//time><rate>2</rate>< text>
For a branch of a Japanese arcade chain, this location sure was lacking in Japanese arcade games, especially compared to other Socal locations like Puente Hills and Santa Ana. I make the drive to those latter two frequently and was ecstatic to hear there would be one in my back yard, but nearly all the games I usually play are either missing, like Final Fantasy Theatrhythm, Dancerush Stardom, Time Crisis, or Luigi's Mansion, or their servers are disconnected, like Groove Coaster.
Instead, the floor is graced with the likes of mobile game ports (more than usual, the most remarkable example being an unwinnable sword duel game with TWO separate cabinets) and gigantic licensed light-gun games that are just cheap knockoffs of their betters (multiple Rabbids and Walking Dead games, a Tomb Raider game with a ten foot high screen, and a Halo game whose cabinet is the size of a large shed and peddles flash level gameplay in temptation of Waypoint rewards). Barely anybody has been on those that I've seen so far.
Perhaps the notion here is that a building full of Japanese games would be too niche for a community like Temecula compared to the significantly more Asian population of the area around Puente Hills, and so they played it safe with a bunch of "normal people" content. I would get where that's coming from, but at the same time, it feels like a huge wasted opportunity. The location is very new though, so I hope they do something with it.

PS: To whoever rigged up the fighting game cabinets in the back, you mixed up the Melty Blood and the Marvel 2 setups. I had a chuckle at that. Good on you for having Melty, though.<//text>

<Rate>4<//Rate><Text>This was a lovely park, with a community center. There are all the basics: picnic tables, bathrooms, a children's playground, a basketball court and a curving paved walk through the beautiful green space. It's "small" (though i have seen smaller) but large enough to have a handful of parking spaces; i believe the steep green hills and irregular curves contribute most to the sense of being in nature.
I wonder how a crowd manages with the restroom (two stalls and one sink for females) in better weather, when more than a handful of people are present in the space. I imagine it's hectic whenever something's going on inside the community center. I'd like to see their schedule of events.</Text><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNUe2r9aMOabZ6abQ2phJKEQMOcii7EEe6FUYuP=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNL_G0hAl32fCfPF64pduh1fiLh_0uFofWBAN4U=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM25kTpmCLpIcB4If-Nj4Y42FRcFbY93xi1-y62=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPh18TMVB99r3tO4SX_51wMLPTRJIAsyC0Rc9hL=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOvINtTQ78IRujcM8EIHlZ4xIp6Jbl-sB5fbyZI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNdn7cyo7Thg1-yqI9I52A1R1Zatjgate2wR2r3=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO1L7kyRcq8K1d5iijlJ5S31MA5SuyglKgt99rI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNg0FDnO4lBga9-giJYeePcxk3tW_IAckCiOWOv=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOYhTjNxUtQ8WiouomvaOBm1jLEzxCbTb9UbUyI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNDd5aONKvCQ0FhwLycuQtv6Z3EMrbnvpjc6bpK=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures><Response>None</Response><gmap_id>0x80dd2cb467ac9c7b:0xe53637bb5f5e624d<//gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

115416100185945382737< /user_id>
<Rating>5</Rating><username>Ken M< /username><Pics>None</Pics><Response>None<//Response><date>1544472788066< /date>< text>
Fear of unknown.
You, in good conscious appear at the court room 102 for a routine traffic ticket. The room gets full and whispering starts at no time, kids hitting your seat, people talking your ears off and suddenly dead silance.

The Deputy Sheriff, so easily and comfortably takes over the room. The next thirty minutes is nothing but the most smooth, humorous, pointing, factual, and noteworthy talk you will ever encounter.

Deputy Marc Lashley, in a very attention grabbing fashion, gets your undivided attention as to what is to be occurring during the court session.

So much so that you really don't care why you are there but pray this half hour talk continue endlessly. It is informative, spoon fed to those intruptive, as well as attorneys, and other attending  officers.

The detailed procedures, options, cost, and all other relative information are well put together and presented by him.

During my two visits, I sat there and watched the ins and outs of this courtroom, and must confess that it is extremely well run, professional and well mannered staff with much kudos to Deputy Lashley who makes the visit far less dry and otherwise tenuous.

Later that day, when I misspoke at another level, in seeking alternatives to correct the situation, visibly at unrest, I met Barbara Padilla, a well dressed, soft spoken supervisor who took time to explain and offer options to remedy my particular case.

I could not have had any better coach who took time, listened to my broken explainiation and walked me through what was at play.

I left the window and the courthouse having met two new friendly advocates to keep for life. Neither had to do what they did. But they did it because of who they are, and what they do.

It all goes to the basic values of treating one another with dignity. I hope, I earned that too. The fear never settled in!</text>

< review>
Sheldon is a rare bird. He is exceptionally knowledgeable, extremely conscientious, and he cares for each piece of audio equipment as if it were his own.

That all said, know that you will be paying a premium price for a premium service, and you will be waiting patiently for this service to be completed. You will get your money's worth, but this kind of meticulous service isn't and shouldn't be cheap or rushed.

My vintage Yamaha CR 2010 receiver went from barely working/sputtering and unreliable at best, to indistinguishable from brand new, rock solid and sounding as good as ever. I look forward to many more years of listening pleasure that I was afraid I'd lost and could never recover.</review>

<rating>5</rating><Text>"You can't hurry art" is what Sheldon told me from the beginning when I took my Marantz 140 amp to him for much needed repair/restoration. Yes, it took a long while, techs this good have quite a backlog of work. I was not in a hurry and never felt anxious about the wait. Once he got to the unit, Sheldon called and gave me two options: repair the actual problem or completely restore the unit innards (the exterior was "pristine"). I opted for the full restoration ("it will be good for another 50 years"). A couple of days later the unit was ready. When I arrived he had it playing. It not only sounded fantastic but also looked even better. Worth the wait and the price. Thank you Sheldon!</Text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Resp>

<pictures>None</pictures><Time>1627532717203<//Time><review>Brought a higher-end Denon amplifier (PMA-A100) for repair (left channel drop out), and Sheldon found a non-obvious problem with a switch to the amplification circuit.  After determining that the part (switch itself) is no longer sold, he rebuilt the broken part, taking steps to strengthen the component well beyond what was provided initially by the manufacturer.   The service was performed within the promised timeframe, and the company was clear and timely in their communication about the project.

In my experience, Champlifier proved to be very knowledgeable and capable, delivering great results at a reasonable price for the hours required to effect the repair. Sheldon made an extra effort to arrange a convenient (after-hours) time for pick-up.

Recommended for audio amplifier services.  Also, great company name!<//review>< Rating>

< Gmap_id>

<Name>Adam W< /Name><resp>None< /resp>< Review>
After giving Champlifier half of a year to make a repair and no work was completed, Champlifier was unfortunately a huge letdown.

When I found Champlifier to fix the cracked mesh on my speaker grills, I was excited by their good reviews and work portfolio. When I initially contacted owner Sheldon, he seemed confident and professional.

However, after I dropped off the speaker grills, things became strange.  First, when I asked Sheldon to provide a quote for the repair, he was extremely reluctant to provide it, saying that it would take him a lot of time and that he would need to charge me for it.  After some time and multiple conversations, and me promising him that I understood that prices in quotes fluctuate, he finally wrote one.  It was a simple quote with two items and a total estimated price - nothing special.  It's baffling that he would expect customers to agree to pay for a repair without a written price estimate and then generally insist on charging a customer for a basic one.

Fast forward six months later, Sheldon had not done any work on the repair and never even proactively provided me with an update.  After sending him emails and calling him, and him dodging me and providing excuses, I decided to pick up the speaker grills.  That day, Sheldon told me that he needed more time.  It does NOT take over six months to source mesh material and glue it on speaker grills.  I used to do model making, have worked on cars, sanded a car to bare metal and consider myself pretty handy overall.  I wanted to save myself some time and support a local business, especially during the pandemic, which has been a challenging time for businesses.

The worst part is that when I finally picked up the speaker grills, he refused to return my deposit despite the fact that he had not done any of the repair in the entire six months he had my grills.  This forced me to contact my credit card company, after which I was informed by a representative that he had told them that the repair was ready to be completed the day I picked up the speakers.  Sheldon lied in order to keep his deposit.

I am very sensitive to the fact we‚Äôre in a pandemic and businesses are experiencing many challenges.  At minimum, Sheldon should have provided me with updates without me having to chase after him and been honest about his inability to do the job when he realized he couldn't or wouldn't do it.

Stay away from Champlifier and save yourself the time, money and hassle.< /Review>

I was starting to fall out of love with my 1975 Luxman l-100u integrated amplifier. This was the flagship of Luxman in its heyday, and it sounded sweet. But then it started to develop a bit of noise and crackle in the right channel, which gradually got worse. I had another shop take a look at it, they claimed to fix it, but no.

The problem was super tricky - intermittent, with all of the components testing in spec. To make matters worse, this is a, extremely complicated amp to work on.

After picking it up, I noted that the problem was almost gone, but not quite. The gremlin came back! Sheldon helped me troubleshoot over the phone and asked to take another look at it.

I picked it up today and have been listening to it for hours, and cannot believe how great it sounds. A completely black and transparent background, and sounding better then it ever has before!

Sheldon was fair and transparent with me on the price. In fact, I know for a fact that he put in many more hours of labor than he charged me for, and a full list of the replaced components along with pics of everything along the way.

Seriously, he is the real deal. A "transistor whisperer" and one who takes the utmost pride in his work. If you want your forever stereo to sound as good or better than the day it left the showroom, Champlifier is a worthwhile investment.< /review>

Although not cheap, it's just like taking one's car to a mechanic, it is quality, precision work on a very rare and top of the line turntable, so I pay what I must to preserve it.  I will going in with a couple of my vintage receivers.

Champlifier is a great asset for folks like me who like good audio gear.  Some may call us audiophiles and that's fine, but there is quite a broad cost/value range when it comes to audio gear, and this is where Sheldon, owner of Champlifier, is so helpful.

He is qualified to work on the really, really expensive stuff, AND he is also qualified and willing to work on the good gear that mere mortals, like me, can afford.  Sheldon is an honest guy, and this matters immensely, because he will let the customer know that a particular repair might not be the most cost-effective solution, that it might be better to get something new, rather than waste time and money on a unit -- even when that is lost business for him.

Sheldon is also a good guide for which units are worthy used ones to look up and which combinations separates and brands make good systems.  I'm old enough to remember going in to real stereo shops and talking with salespeople who knew this same hi-fi secret sauce, but that knowledge has been lost until now.  Highly recommended.

< review>
I have a 45 year old McIntosh amp which I brought into Champlifier. I could not be happier with the end result. One channel was out and the poor unit had lived in Hawaii for 25 years, which is a very unkind place for electronics. Not only did Sheldon expertly restore it to working order, he went above and beyond to do so. He even buffed up the wood case.
Unfortunately, I foolishly shorted out the darn thing when I got it home. After Sheldon patiently trouble shot the problem over the phone, i took it back in. Fuses were replaced and I learned more proper care and safety so that this would not happen again. I ended up purchasing his individually made speaker wire hook ups which are perfect for my amp and speakers. Having had the piece so many years, I thought I knew what I was doing. Lessons learned.
Sheldon is an expert. He is meticulous and is a very good teacher, patient and never condescending.
Be prepared to leave your property a good while so that he may do it right. Trust me. It‚Äôs definitely worth it.< /review>

A few days later he called me with a diagnostic and suggestions.  A few days later I had my fixed mixer back. The next day he was calling to ask about how it was performing!

I really appreciate how Sheldon explains everything in a clear, patient, straightforward way. He's talented and passionate about electronics and is a pleasure to be around in general. He even fixed two janky speaker inputs for free. He's really organized and available too. You can call or text him pretty much anytime. He e-mailed me to let me know work had started on my mixer, and then after it was done, he e-mailed me a copy of the invoice.

As far as price, it's reasonable. Yes, I could have purchased another cheap mixer for the cost of the fix, but that's just the thing.  It would be cheap, with another worthless fan, and bound to break somehow in a year or two. Not a lot of people work on this kind of stuff, especially for Sheldon's rates, and they certainly don't have fast turn arounds.  Peace of mind is priceless.  Now I know I can haul all my gear anywhere and it'll work like a *champ.* Yeah, really glad I found this place. I'll be back whenever I have a problem with any of my gear.<//review>< pics>

<Rating>1< /Rating><Review>This really is interesting to see all these 5 star reviews on this business.. Because my experience was quite different ..  While the work was good (its not a terribly difficult job)   the cost of repair , without question in my mind ,  is exorbitant to put it nicely. I thought I would give this business a chance.   About 8 mos ago there was a bit of a red flag regarding the owner not responding to an inquiry I had. I did not heed that gut feeling to go somewhere else.    Due to a number of shops that had recommended I thought I would bring a tuner in that simply had 2 bulbs burnt out and indicated to replace only the 2 bulbs.   And  this person  took it upon them self to replace a third which did not need replacing.     Normally I would do this myself and in fact had replaced a couple of bulbs in this tuner previously.  Mind you this is not rocket science.  The meter bulbs are accessible with the simple removal of 6 screws on the bottom cover plate.  Remove that cover and the bulbs are right there.  not hidden, not buried. right there .   So ok.   How long does it take to solder a couple of wires to a bulb and put the little assembly back into the slot?  I'm not a stranger to this type of work.  As I noted,  I've had this tuner apart including removal of the front face plate to replace dial bulbs.   A tech is literally looking at 20 minutes .. Ok.  so lets give an hour.    It's not difficult at all to get an idea of how long a simple job like this should take when I have done the same thing myself and  when one is familiar with working on cars,  electronics ,,etc..   I was charged $212 ..  That my friends is ,, by even bay area standards  is way above what constitutes a  fair price.  At least the job was done right-- at least so far.   But that can not justify how much it cost to replace a couple of bulbs  and a piece of wire  6 inches long maybe---(that was 10 bucks)   bulbs were $8 each x 3 = $24 for 3 sm meter bulbs!
3 bulbs and a piece of wire .    Let me give an analogy  and see if this resonates in terms of getting ones moneys worth.  Just so its clear that I dont have a problem spending the money.      I had a McIntosh vintage tuner completely gone through and restored by a Mac authorized tech who has been in the business for more than 30  years.  This was a complete restoration including any updates that the factory noted needed to be done.   that job was 500 and change.  A friend was quoted $180 for a complete alignment including tuning pot replacement from Magnum Dynalab. ( a very involved technical service requiring electronic test instruments and the skill to match)   In comparison   this shop would of charged me upwards of $1k to restore my Mac if he is going to charge $212 to replace 3 bulbs.
Do yourself a favor.  Try L&M electronics,  Daly City,   Genes Audio (house calls)   , even Handy TV repair on University in Berkeley.. He mostly works on tv's but does some audio as well.  And I see there appear to be a couple more places.  Erik in Alameda,  Bruce in Berkeley.  Whatever you do don't go here.
People need to know .    I am respecting Google though for keeping my review in the que.    Yelp kicked  my review to the not recommended reviews page along with 1 or 2 others.   The reason ---because I am not an active part of the Yelp community is what I am able to discern reading their FAQ.</Review><pictures>None</pictures><response>None</response><GmapID>0x808f80c57047c039:0x13a0b3652aadac6b< /GmapID></record>

< Name>
Chang Yi< /Name>
< Date>
1402428245403<//Date>
<rate>5</rate>< review>
Champlifier is really the best audio technician service in the Bay Area. Sheldon, the owner, personally oversees or works on your equipment. Whether you have a boutique English solid state amplifier or a classic Marantz receiver, Sheldon will go above and beyond to acquire the schematics, parts, or accessories, whether from the manufacturer, third party parts dealers or even Ebay.

I brought Sheldon a number of items through the years, including two NAD receivers, a pair of Rogers LS6 (BBC spec) speakers, and QSC amplifiers. I tried taking the Rogers LS6 to a competing audio technician in North Oakland. Boy was that a mistake. That technician had no idea what a Rogers BBC spec speaker was all about. In fact, he tried to replace my woofer and cone with a Sony replacement. WTF?! So of course, I was fuming mad and disillusioned with technicians acting like they know their audio history and technology.

When I brought it to Sheldon, he knew right away what was wrong. He pointed out the dust cap, which was becoming unglued and causing a rattle sound. No cone or driver replacement necessary! Not only did he save me money, but gave me tips as to how to replace it myself with over the counter glue from Michael's.

My last item that I brought to Sheldon, a NAD 7100 amplifier, was just as exceptional. It had some issues with the logic board that I didn't know about. It kept cutting out on one channel, and the tuner was spotty. The tuner wouldn't turn on somedays. I finally got tired of the solid state amp and brought it in. Sheldon couldn't find the issue, as the amp decided to work when it was in Sheldon's possession for a week. He charged me the $35 inspection fee, and I brought it home. Lo and behold, the NAD 7100's tuner stopped working completely. Anyone who knows the NAD amp series knows the tuner is precise and crystal clear. So, I had to bring the NAD amp back to Sheldon. He set aside the $35 inspection fee and told me he would have it fixed in three weeks.

Three weeks later, Sheldon gave me a perfectly working NAD 7100 amplifier. He had hunted a broken NAD 7100 on Ebay. Taken out the broken logic board piece. Put in the logic board from the Ebay NAD 7100 and completely restored my NAD amplifier with 100% original parts. The final bill was less than $45. In one word, exceptional.

I trust Sheldon as an honest professional that will give you the best technical skills and personal service. I have been blown away by his work. (again my issues were mostly with solid state amps, which is hard to get fixed at typical musician repair shops) And I cannot recommend Sheldon enough to everyone I know.</review>

< Text>
About two months ago I brought a vintage Kenwood Eleven GX to sheldon to repair the right channel that was intermittent.  There were also several lights on this old 70's stereo receiver.  Sheldon was friendly and professional.   I could tell when I walked into his shop that I was in the right place because his work area was neat and orderly.  Everything was organized and put in the proper place.  I also saw other vintage expensive gear on the shelves.   I could tell this was not his job, but he was passionate about what he does and takes care of every piece like it is his own.

Several day later he fixed my Receiver and it  sounds and looks great.   He also did an LED conversion on this unit that took him a while because of the age, but it looked like a piece of art when he was done.

Since then I have brought in my Yamaha M-2 amp (1978 vintage 240 watts a ch) to have the bulbs replaced and a a routine check up.    Was turned around in a short time and looks and sounds great.

I also brought Sheldon my Yamaha R-1000 receiver (Vintage 1982)  and he replaced several bulbs and capacitors.   It's like the day they were born, revived and ready to go for another 40 years.

I would recommend Champlifer to any friend or family member.

You rock Sheldon!< /Text>

<Time>1383591899377<//Time><pictures>None< /pictures>< review>
I don't have much words to say except that I brought my Krell KSA-100 amp into Champlifier with a lot of doubt. My amp had a loud pop and smoke and smell were coming out of the amp. I didn't want to send the Krell to Krell Service because I know that they would charge a pretty huge sum of money plus they require you to have the original box.

Taking a chance on Sheldon from Champlfier, I left my amp there for about 3 weeks. Sheldon was very attentive and took time with customers. He called me up for quotes and give detailed explaination of what went wrong with the amp. Basically, a lot of the power transistors on one channel just went out. He had to do a replacement of all of the transistors on one channel. I still had doubt that the amp would sound the same with what he was doing. Mind you that this is a Class A amp. However, Sheldon proved me wrong. The amp, after repair, sounded perfect. Not only that all the power transistors that Sheldon replaced were perfect match with the original transistors. Sheldon also did a few re-cap of the capicitors for me that was too old. The cost was not cheap but reasonable.

He also detected a problem with the power switch for me and had it fixed for free. I keep telling Sheldon that we need more people like him and it's a blessing that I was able to find him and that he should be in the business of amp fixing and he should never quit. He bring joy to a lot of audiophiles.<//review>

< text>
I can definitely see why they have such good reviews. This office was referred to me by a friend after a traumatic experience with my previous dentist. My first visit was for an emergency tooth extraction.

The dentist and hygienist who worked with me were professional, kind, understanding, and patient. The dentist sat down with me and told me about what my options were and told me what she thought we should do. She was tactful and calm with me, and did everything in her power to calm me down.

Honestly, I have enough dental anxiety that the only way I could be calm during a visit is if I'm sedated, and I didn't have enough time between my call and the visit to get the medication for that. The website says it is something they offer, and I'll have to ask.

They put on soothing ocean sounds, they were calm and cheered me on the whole way, they spoke to me encouragingly, laid things out easily, and were overall incredibly professional and kind through the whole experience.

I plan to call back and set up a plan to get the rest of my dental work done. I really love this office. The receptionists are on top of things and very thorough. I would recommend this office to everyone I speak to!</text>

<Review>I had veneers done on my 2 front teeth from another dentist 18 months prior. Not long after they were installed, my right-front veneer cracked and actually chipped away from the top of the tooth at the gums.

Let me tell you, I have not had great experiences with dentists ever since I broke my 2 front teeth at the age of 6. <user>118029653875114720669</user>< username>
Marianne Kearney-Brown</username>
< date>
1594265573227< /date>
<Rating>1< /Rating><Text>DON'T BUY FLOORING AT HOME DEPOT!!!!!!!!!!!!

On June 3, 2020, I went to Home Depot for laminate flooring. All the signs said "8 Day Delivery if Not in Stock", so I assumed that the flooring would be delivered within two weeks. The flooring has to stay in the house for a few days before it can be installed, then two or three days for the install.  Even with a week extra, it fit my timeline and I paid for flooring and installation.

The sales guy was very helpful, and I got a phone call updating me on what would happen. It all seemed good.

Two weeks come and go. No flooring and no word. I call. They say they will get back to me. I call again. They finally get back to me-the flooring will arrive on July 2, 2020. (Four weeks from the order date.)  The installation will be a week later.

Two days before the delivery they call. The delivery window is 8 AM to 6 PM. They did not tell me that the "delivery" would be to my yard. If I had known that, I would have had someone on call to help me. I did not know that, so I had to unload a full pallet of laminate from the yard into the basement all by myself OR leave it in the yard for someone to steal.

At age 62, I unload a full pallet of laminate from my yard to the basement.

So now, today, we are at week five. The installers are set to arrive between 8 AM- 10 AM. They arrive at 12:05.

Twenty minutes later, the installers say the floors are far to unlevel and there is no way to install them. They pack up and leave.

Five weeks in and Home Depot is telling me "Oh, well, these things happen." I said "You sent out a guy to measure and assess! He told me the floors were level!!!"  The customer service person says "Well, he really can't tell, the installers are the ones who can tell..."

If I have known on June 3 that an installer would show up 5-1/2 weeks later to tell me the job was impossible, I never would have paid Home Depot $4,700.

UPDATE: I had a contractor friend come in to level it. He says there should be no problem, it's just a couple of places. He says those guys probably did not want to carry the laminate up from the basement.

DON'T BUY FLOORING AT HOME DEPOT!!!!!!!!!!!!<//Text>< pictures>
None</pictures>

<gmapID>0x80850611d5cb0cb3:0x58c5886cbf8786b3<//gmapID>< Review>
My experience with the custom cabinetry department, particularly when you've made an appointment, is 5 stars. This review is for every other experience I've had at this Home Depot.

Finding help in the store is very difficult, and the quality if the help when found is hit and miss. More often miss. Finding specific items is time consuming because everything is very poorly labeled. Many items are in the the wrong location. Many items are damaged. The store layout is horrible, made much worse by the fact that they cram things into every aisle.

Many items are well priced, but many are overpriced. All in all, if I need advice I go elsewhere. If I know exactly what I need and where it is located, I go there. If I know what I need but not where it is, I go but know that I will be there for 2 hours.</Review>

< Text>
After being a loyal customer for nearly 30 years and spending in excess of  200,000 dollars on my home projects and always enjoying my shopping experience and dealing with the most helpful home depot employees. I have had my worst retail experience in my life today at the Napa Home depot store. 3/8/2015 at 3:00pm. I started on a project approx 6 weeks ago and have spent to date 9,000$ on my home depot account in a couple of the surrounding Home depot's. Today I had a return of approx $250 worth of extra materials and had the unfortunate encounter with Karen in the Napa store. Simply wanted to return the materials and receive an in store credit on my account. To which she said I would need to return the items to the store they were purchased in. To simplify things I suggested she just issue a store credit. She was condescending and rude. She should not be representative of home depot. After the transaction she continued to be very unprofessional and down right rude. I intend on taking this miserable experience to corporate tomorrow. <Time>1400017951946<//Time><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Response>None< /Response><GmapID>0x80850611d5cb0cb3:0x58c5886cbf8786b3< /GmapID>< Name>

< user_id>
118396066521175690859<//user_id>
<review>Without question, the Napa Home Depot store has got to be the WORST as it relates to customer service!  From the employees ambulating aimlessly around the store (everywhere indeed, except where they need to be when one needs to find them!)

We have done a couple of remodels in the last 5 years. One of them working with the Salt Lake City Fort Union store, the other in and around the Napa Valley. What a difference in work ethic, level of knowledge, and willingness to help on the part of the employees at both stores!!! While the SLC employees in all departments were courteous, went out of their way to help, and knew their stuff, the people at the Napa store --whenever one can find someone-- were apathetic, dumb and even dismissive.

Just yesterday, I went to ask a simple question at the paint dept. and could find no one behind the desk. When I did find somebody in one of the aisles, the guy spoke broken English and answered my questions with a sneering attitude.

I'll be politically incorrect here and just get to the point in the interest of brevity and truth: The fact is most of the employees seem to have been picked from one minority or another, perhaps to satisfy the obligatory quota system prevailing in this NorCal-Frisco-values-infected enclave. Unfortunately, the impression these people project is that they are either resentful of being employed, or that they are there strictly for an easy ride and a paycheck. They show absolutely no sense of commitment to their job.

Perhaps there's a pervasive lack of competence as well in the managerial pool, since apparently no one appears to be checking up on these poorly supervised employees who exhibit little time for customers, yet plenty of it for chit-chating and yucking it up with one another, for spending time talking on their cell phone, or for walking around with their hands inside their apron pockets.

I have finally opted to  avoid these Napa HD store 'human drones' and drive to Windsor or Rhonert Park to get better service. Even considering the additional expense in gas, the travel time, the higher Sonoma County tax rate, and half-spaced-out pot heads who work there, the Santa Rosa HD is slightly preferable.

Bottom line, Home Depot headquarters should do some sort of employe proficiency and motivation audit on the Napa store employees to improve this situation. Perhaps the only reason this store does not close, given the enormous waste and inefficiency that occurs there, is the fact that this is the only HD in the middle of a mostly rural area, and this perhaps helps to keep the sales volume consistently high. However, there's no reason the customers should have to suffer the inconvenience of having to travel afar to get satisfaction. I'd give this store ZERO stars, but the system in place does not allow it!

PS: Additionally, I am working with highly sought-after contractors on the current remodel, and they have made it abundantly clear to me that they will not do business with the Napa HD store, precisely for the reasons explained above!</review></record>
